State in 1-2 paragraphs how you would control for quality.  What measurements would you take in order to make a case that this project was of high quality?

In order to control quality, we will hold meetings at least once a week and compare our deliverables against the requirements. If there are any discrepancies we will fix them immediately. We will also perform 3 types of testing: 1) unit testing, making sure every part of our system is working correctly before moving on to the next one; 2) integration testing, we will check for integration between each component of our system, so they work tightly together; 3) user acceptance testing, after we published our project, we will verify the operation of the game is smooth and our participants can solve our game in a logical order. In addition, we will also maintain our budget and remove extraneous costs.

Risks

Risk
Mitigation Plan
Development Time Constraints
A clear and structured time management chart is created using the Gantt Chart method. This will help the project manager keep an up-to-date look at what stage the project should be at any given time during the duration of the project. Clear channels of communication as outlined in the Communications Covenant also aid the project manager in gaining feedback from the developers should they fall behind from the schedule.
Unfamiliar Platform
None of the team members are completely familiar with web development platforms. To mitigate this, we have chosen one of the most widely used rapid web application development platforms, Rails. The Rails community provides many tutorials and guides to aid in the learning of the platform for free. This should make learning the platform easy.
User Adoption
Since this project introduces a fairly new concept of augmented reality puzzle games to the UCI campus, it may be difficult to gain a user base. In order to mitigate this, we have developed a clear marketing strategy to promote the deployment of the game; furthermore, we have incorporated a rewards system as well as a competition mechanism to gain loyalty.
Unforeseen Costs
Given the unknown nature of user adoption, and the dynamic real-world nature of the game, the project is at risk of incurring unforeseen costs. Possible costs can be related to fines related to property, as well as litigation from those who have been hurt while playing the game. To mitigate this, we will check with the locations where we will be posting our real-world puzzle pieces to make sure that it is authorized. Also, a disclaimer will be posted on the website to exempt us from the liability of any health-related incidents that can occur while playing the game.


Quality

In order to control quality, we will hold meetings at least once a week to report our progress and compare our deliverables against the requirements. If there are any discrepancies we will identify the exact problem and fix it immediately within the week. We will also perform 3 types of testing: 
1) Unit testing-this is where we will make sure every part of our system is working correctly before moving on to the next one
2) Integration testing- this is where we will check for integration between each component of our system, to ensure each component fit well together with the other.
3) User acceptance testing - after we published our project, we will verify the operation of the game is smooth and our participants can solve our game in a logical order. Finally, we will maintain our budget continuously and remove extraneous costs where possible.

In the case that quality is extremely compromised, we will hold meetings and discuss the measures we can take to fix the problems. We shall try to uphold a one week deadline for fixing our problems. The measurements we take to determine whether our project is of high quality includes participants satisfaction, participation rate, success rate as defined by the number of people who start the game compared to the person that finish it. We will derive this information from our database. This information will be based on an analysis of the number of people who are registered and the people who are posted on the leader board.
